{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f3d1dec1-e424-4132-bc3f-b01f5b9d628b","content":"`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` tells the layout not to add safe-area padding, but you also need to handle **platform-specific** window chrome. Here's what's likely missing:\n\n### 1. Hide the MAUI navigation bar\n```xml\nShell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n<!-- or if using NavigationPage: -->\nNavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"\n```\n\n### 2. iOS — disable safe area insets on the page\n```xml\n<ContentPage\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n### 3. Android — render behind system bars\nIn your `MainActivity.cs` or a handler, enable edge-to-edge and make system bars transparent:\n\n```csharp\n#if ANDROID\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\n// In your activity or window setup:\nWindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\nWindow.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\nWindow.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n#endif\n```\n\nOn Android 15+ (API 35), apps are edge-to-edge by default, but the bars may still have a scrim — setting transparent colors removes it.\n\n### Putting it together\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"...\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"\n             Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\">\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**TL;DR:** `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` handles the MAUI layout layer, but iOS safe-area insets and Android system-bar decor are separate platform concerns that need their own opt-outs.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6458f729-a9c6-4b9d-9bf6-5533024ece6b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI full-screen/edge-to-edge display. They want an image to go behind the status bar and navigation bar, filling the entire screen. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still have padding.\n\nThis is a .NET MAUI question about edge-to-edge rendering. In .NET 10 (which would be a preview as of May 2026), there have been changes to how edge-to-edge display works, particularly on Android.\n\nLet me think about what I know:\n\nIn .NET MAUI (.NET 9+), there's been work on edge-to-edge support. The key things to know:\n\n\n- `SafeAreaEdges` on `ContentPage` controls whether the page respects safe area insets, but setting it to \"None\" alone might not be sufficient.\n- On Android, starting with Android 15 (API 35), apps are edge-to-edge by default, though the system bars still overlay the content.\n- The real issue is that the user probably needs to configure how the system bars interact with the app content, not just disable safe area padding.\n- On Android, they'll need to make the status bar and navigation bar transparent through platform-specific code or by adjusting their colors.\n- On iOS, `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` should generally work, but they might need to ensure the image layout itself ignores safe area constraints.\n- In .NET MAUI, properties like `Page.IgnoreSafeArea` or the `SafeArea` attached property might be more relevant than just `SafeAreaEdges`.\n- For iOS specifically, using the platform-specific namespace to set `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` on the ContentPage is likely the cleaner approach.\n- For Android edge-to-edge layouts, they need to handle the system bars through platform-specific configuration.\n\nLet me reconsider what's actually available in the current .NET versions. The `SafeAreaEdges` property helps control padding around safe areas, but on Android that's only part of the solution—the window itself needs to be configured to render behind the system bars. On iOS, the `UseSafeArea` setting is the key control. For a true edge-to-edge photo viewer experience, I need to address both the page-level safe area handling and the platform-specific window configuration. I need to be more precise about what's actually available. The core issue is that `SafeAreaEdges` alone won't give them full edge-to-edge rendering—they need platform-specific handling on both iOS and Android to make the system bars transparent and allow content to extend behind them. On Android 15+, edge-to-edge might be the default, but they still need to ensure the bars themselves are transparent rather than just letting content flow behind opaque bars.","outputTokens":1843,"requestId":"B80F:1EC425:19EB18:2199F5:69FFDAF0"},"id":"3df4cecf-22a9-4983-bff6-ce3a0e7038ae","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:10:42.825Z","parentId":"2b0e1cfd-c380-4c36-a92f-ba43e1be8dbb"}
